1 Setup
*******

  1. *Install Lean* version 4.  You can follow the official “manual
     (https://lean-lang.org/install/manual/)” instructions because V.
     S.  Code is not needed.

  2. *Install Nael* packages.  For example, clone the Git repository
     that contains the packages and add the path of desired packages to
     ‘load-path’ variable in your Emacs user initialisation file:

          git clone https://codeberg.org/mekeor/nael ~/path/to/nael

          (add-to-list 'load-path "~/path/to/nael/nael")
          ;; (add-to-list 'load-path "~/path/to/nael/nael-lsp")
          ;; (add-to-list 'load-path "~/path/to/nael/nael-markdown")

  3. Optionally, install Nael manuals.  This is so you can read the
     readme/manual from within Emacs.

          (require 'info)
          (info-initialize)
          (add-to-list 'Info-directory-list "~/path/to/nael/nael")

  4. *Load Nael* features.  You can either load the features eagerly
     whenever Emacs is started, or load them lazily, i.e.  defer the
     actual loading to the first time a Lean source file is opened.

          ;; Option 1, eager loading:
          (require 'nael)
          ;; (require 'nael-lsp)
          ;; (require 'nael-markdown)

          ;; Option 2, lazy loading:
          (require 'nael-autoloads)
          ;; (require 'nael-lsp-autoloads)

  5. Optionally, configure Nael.  For example, enables abbreviations as
     well as LSP automatically:

          (add-hook 'nael-mode-hook #'abbrev-mode)
          (add-hook 'nael-mode-hook #'eglot-ensure)


