2 Usage
*******

Language Server Protocol (LSP):

   • To start an LSP client automatically, configure ‘nael-mode-hook’.
     To start one interactively, type ‘C-c C-e’ (‘eglot’), or, if you
     have installed ‘nael-lsp’, ‘C-c C-l’ (‘lsp’).

   • ‘C-h .’ (‘eldoc-doc-buffer’) displays the ElDoc documentation
     buffer showing tactic state and expected goal at point.

   Abbreviations:

   • To enable abbreviations automatically, configure ‘nael-mode-hook’.
     To enable them interactively, type ‘C-c C-a’ (‘abbrev-mode’).

   • ‘C-c C-k’ (‘nael-abbrev-help’) will tell you how the abbreviation
     for the active region or character at point.

   • Note that Nael's Abbrev tables use the ‘:regexp’ property which is
     (https://github.com/minad/cape/discussions/158#discussioncomment-14687758)
     neither compatible with Company nor Cape.  For completion at point,
     ‘nael-abbrev’ defines ‘nael-abbrev-capf’ which is buffer-locally
     added to ‘completion-at-point-functions’ whenever Abbrev mode is
     enabled inside Nael.  To ditch this CAPF, set the
     ‘nael-abbrev-capf’ variable to ‘nil’.

   Emacs commands beyond Nael:

   • ‘C-c C-c’ or equally ‘C-x p c’ (‘project-compile’) suggests ‘lake
     build’ as command to build the current project.
   • ‘M-g i’ (‘imenu’) jumps to a interactively chosen definition in
     current buffer.
   • ‘M-;’ (‘comment-dwim’) will toggle active region as comment or, if
     no region is active, create a comment at end of line.
   • ‘M-q’ (‘prog-fill-reindent-defun’) will fill the string- or
     comment-paragraph at point, or reindent the point-surrounding code.


